title: For Sale:  Diamondback DB9, lightest, smallest 9mm available
postcontent: Hello everyone, I have a Diamondback DB9 for sale.  Good condition, 2-6rd mags, talon grips.  These guns are the lightest and smallest 9mm available.  The company had some trouble with these when they first came out, but it looks like they have worked out the bugs.  These are super easy to conceal and fairly accurate despite the size.  They can be a handful and are more for advanced users, not a first gun.  Full disclosure:  on round 197 one of the trigger springs broke.  I was firing factory new Remington 9mm JHP at the time, but 2 rounds of the magazine felt "hot" and it was on the second "hot" round that the issue occurred.  I cannot say it was loaded to higher pressure, but it did feel like it.  These guns are designed to work with .124 gr or .115 gr and no +P.  In any event, Diamondback fixed it in a few weeks and I put it through its paces.  The first week back I put 500 rounds down range and it went without a hitch.  I have another DB9 that I carry and it is up to 500-600 rounds with no issues.  This gun is a great gun that is about the size and weight of a .380 but with 9mm punch.  It disappears in a pocket and will go places larger guns can't.  Looking to fund other projects, so no trades right now please.  If interested, please call Don, REDACTED.  Please be 21 or older with current gun permit or we can meet at Warrior Arms in Valpo for transfer.  Thanks for looking, and have a great night.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Lee Straight Pull Sporting .236 USN 24"
location: North carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: This auction is for the Winchester Lee Straight Pull Sporting Rifle shown. Caliber is .236 USN. The Winchester Lee Straight Pull Sporting Rifle was the sporting version of the Winchester Lee M1895 Navy rifle designed by James Paris Lee and featured a unique straight pull bolt design. The .236 USN chambering was a hot rod of it's day and was known to be a barrel burner. The Lee rifles were not well received and very few were made between 1897 and 1902. Only about 1700 of the sporting versions were made. The S/N of this rifle is 14428 indicating that it was made in 1899. The overall condition of this rifle is very good. The rifle retains much of its original blued finish with edge wear and thinning. It is taking on a gray brown patina. The finger groove walnut stock is very good with some dings from use and a scrape from the action of the bolt, but no cracks. The original steel butt plate is worn to gray with some marks from use. The bore is remarkably good, clean with strong rifling. The unique Lee straight pull action seems to function fine. Overall, a very nice example of this hard to find rifle. C&R OK. NO RESERVE!! Thanks for looking.
